  doi = {10.1111/j.1479-828X.1994.tb02681.x},
  abstract = {Summary: The purpose of this study was to determine the prevalence of postnatal depression (PND) and to assess self-esteem in the early postnatal period and at 6 weeks postpartum and PND at 6 months postpartum. Women giving birth to term babies over a 6-month period, completed an Edinburgh postnatal depression scale (EPDS) and a Rosenberg self-esteem scale in hospital, at 6 weeks postpartum and an EPDS only at 6 months postpartum. A total of 235 women participated in the study of which 222 (95\%) returned their questionnaire at 6 weeks postpartum and 192 (82\%) at 6 months postpartum. Characteristics of the women and their pregnancy outcome are presented. The EPDS identified a depressed mood in 9\% of women in hospital and at 6 weeks postpartum (95\% CI 5.3\%-12.8\%). At 6 months this had increased to 10\% (95\% CI 7.8\%-12.2\%). Postnatal depression was significantly correlated with low self-esteem in hospital and at 6 weeks postpartum. Copyright \textcopyright{} 1994, Wiley Blackwell. All rights reserved},
